Claims The claimed invention is: 1 . A nozzle cleaning system useful for removing a residue of paint or another coating type, comprising: a road vehicle on which a plurality of tanks are mounted for use on the vehicle; one or more hydraulic sprayers each mounted for powered operation on the vehicle to send a coating through a spray gun; one or more feed lines each having a first end connected to a mounted sprayer and extendable from the sprayer at least 100 feet away from the vehicle, each feed line having a first end connectable to a spray gun to spray a coating through a nozzle and on to a surface; a canister positioned on the vehicle for cleaning the nozzle, the cannister having a chamber, an opening for receiving the nozzle into the chamber and a plurality of orifices positioned to spray liquid into the chamber; a container for holding the liquid and mounted on the vehicle; a pump mounted on the vehicle, connected to receive the liquid from the container and connected to provide a high pressure stream of the liquid to the orifices and spray the liquid through the orifices; 2. The system of claim 1 where the orifices are positioned about the chamber so that, when the nozzle is positioned in the chamber for cleaning, the orifices direct a plurality of sprays at a variety of angles about the nozzle to clean coating from an inside portion of the nozzle with the sprays. 3. The system of claim 1 where application of the plurality of sprays dislodges the residual coating material along the inside of the nozzle 612. 4. The system of claim 1 where the orifices are arranged in the cannister so that cleaning can be facilitated by rotation of the nozzle in the container. 5. The system of claim 1 where the orifices are arranged in the cannister so that the nozzle may be cleaned without rotation with respect to the canister. 6. The system of claim 1 where the canister includes a drain to receive liquid from the sprays, the system further including a gravity feed holding tank coupled to receive liquid from the drain. 7. The system of claim 6 where the pump is a pressure washer. 8. A nozzle cleaning system, comprising: a canister having a chamber, an opening for receiving the nozzle into the chamber and a plurality of orifices positioned to spray liquid into the chamber; a pump connected to receive the liquid and provide a high pressure stream of the liquid through the orifices to spray the liquid through the orifices where the orifices are positioned about the chamber so that, when the nozzle is positioned in the chamber for cleaning, the orifices direct a plurality of sprays at a variety of angles about the nozzle to remove coating from an inside portion of the nozzle with the sprays. 9. The system of claim 8 where the orifices are arranged about the cannister so that the nozzle may be cleaned without rotation with respect to the canister. 10. A method for performing a nozzle cleaning operation at a work site, the nozzle being of the type used to spray paint or another coating on a surface, comprising: a) providing spray coating equipment mounted for operation on a vehicle, including a tank from which the coating is drawn for application to a surface at a location away from the vehicle via hoses extending from the vehicle to the location of the surface; b) injecting pressurized liquid, received from a pump mounted on the vehicle, through a plurality of orifices to an interior region of a canister also mounted on the vehicle; c) inserting the nozzle into the interior region of the canister to simultaneously receive multiple sprays emitted by the orifices to clean residual coating from an inside of the nozzle. 11. The method of claim 10, wherein the pump draws the liquid from a holding tank mounted on the vehicle. 12. The method of claim 10, wherein the pressurized water is received from a pressure washer mounted on the vehicle. 13. The method of claim 10, further including, prior to injecting pressurized liquid, spraying paint from the nozzle while the nozzle is installed on a spray gun attached to an end of a spray hose coupled to receive the coating from the equipment mounted on the vehicle. 14. The method of claim 10, further including rotating the inserted nozzle within the interior of the container to direct pressurized liquid on the nozzle from multiple angles and dislodge residual paint from the spray gun nozzle. 15. The method of claim 10, wherein the pressurized liquid is injected at a pressure of approximately 4000 PSI. 16. The method of claim 10, further including draining the liquid from the canister to a holding tank mounted on the vehicle. 17. A mobile cleaning system for paint equipment comprising: a vehicle including a component to perform a paint project at a job site; a pressure washer on the vehicle configured to draw water from a first holding tank on the paint vehicle; a pressure washer valve between the pressure washer and the component such that the pressure washer is configured to deliver pressurized water to the component to clean the component when the pressure washer valve is in an open position; and a second holding tank on the vehicle configured to receive the pressurized water used to clean the component. 18. The system of claim 17, wherein the component is a spray gun nozzle on an end of a hose reel configured to spray paint at the job site. 19. The system of claim 18, wherein the system further includes an open canister configured to receive the pressurized water from the pressure washer and wherein the spray gun nozzle is configured to be inserted within the open canister to clean the spray gun nozzle. 20. The system of claim 17, wherein the component is a paint filter of a paint sprayer positioned on the vehicle. 21. The system of claim 17, wherein the component is an inside surface of a tank positioned on the vehicle for holding paint. 22. The system of claim 17, wherein the component is an exterior of the paint vehicle. 23. A method of providing a liquid coating for application to surfaces from a coating operations vehicle, comprising: 

 providing a vehicle having plurality of tanks for dispensing the liquid mounted thereon, the vehicle including a plurality of hydraulic sprayers mounted on the vehicle for powered operation to dispense the liquid from the mounted tanks when applying the liquid to a surface via a plurality of feed lines connected to extend from the mounted sprayers to a distance away from the vehicle where the coating is to be applied; positioning the vehicle at a location at which a supply of the coating is present for transfer into the tanks; providing a pumping system to transfer the coating from the supply to the tanks while the tanks are mounted on the vehicle, the pumping system including one or more draw tubes; providing a manifold connected between the pumping system and the tanks, the manifold including multiple fill lines, each extending to one of the tanks; and positioning a fill valve in each fill line for (i) control of flow of the coating into at least one of the tanks or (ii) selection of a tank for receipt of the coating material, said control and selection enabling transfer of different coating types into different tanks via the one or more draw tubes. 24. The method of claim 23 further including pumping the coating into one or more of the tanks via the manifold and monitoring the level of coating within at least one tank with a sensor unit which measures the level of coating within the tank and transmits a signal to the pumping system when the level of coating material in the tank is at a desired level in order to deactivate the pumping system. 25. The method of claim 23 further including pumping the coating into one or more of the tanks via the manifold, where the pumping system is applied to transfer the coating from multiple containers each having a nominal holding capacity of at least five gallons, wherein the step of pumping the coating comprises using the pumping system to transfer the coating through the one or more draw tubes and into multiple tanks on the vehicle. 26. The method of claim 25 further including, for each of multiple ones of the containers from which coating is transferred, removing residual coating remaining in the containers, after transfer of the coating through the one or more draw tubes, and transferring the residual coating into at least one tank. 27. The method of claim 26 wherein transferring the residual coating includes consolidating the residual coating acquired from the multiple ones of the containers before transferring the residual coating into the at least one tank. 28. The method of claim 26 wherein transferring the residual coating material into the at least one tank is performed with the pumping system. 29. The method of claim 26 wherein at least three percent of the volume of coating provided in the totality of containers is transferred into at least one tank as residual coating collected from individual ones of the containers. 30. The method of claim 23 wherein the step of pumping the coating material from the supply is performed at a minimum rate of two gallons per minute. 31. The method of claim 23 wherein the step of pumping the coating material from the supply is performed at a minimum rate of five gallons per minute. 32. The method of claim 23 wherein the step of pumping the coating from the supply transfers at least five gallons of coating material into the manifold in 45 seconds. 33. The method of claim 23 further including, after transferring coating into one of the tanks, providing a layer of water to cover the coating material. 34. The method of claim 33 wherein the layer of water is of sufficient volume that when most of the coating material is removed from the tank during a spraying operation and the water enters one of the feed lines the water passes through a spray nozzle before the associated hydraulic paint sprayer draws air from the tank. 35. A method of dispensing liquid coating for spray application of a coating to one or more surfaces, comprising: a) providing a coating operations vehicle on which a plurality of tanks are mounted for dispensing coating from the vehicle, the tanks being filled with coating material to a predetermined level, the vehicle further comprising a plurality of hydraulic sprayers mounted for powered operation on the vehicle and a plurality of hose lines connected to extend from the mounted sprayers to dispense the coating material a distance away from the vehicle; and b) providing a first input manifold connected between multiple ones of the tanks and at least a first of the hydraulic sprayers, the first input manifold including a plurality of manifold input lines, each connected to receive flow of coating from one of the tanks, and at least one output line connected between 

 the manifold input lines and at least one of the hydraulic sprayers to carry flow of coating from the manifold input lines to at least one of the hydraulic sprayers mounted on the vehicle. 36. The method of claim 35 including providing one or more additional input manifolds, each additional input manifold including a plurality of additional manifold input lines and at least one output line, each additional input manifold also connected to receive flow of coating from one of the tanks, and the at least one output line connected between at least one of the manifold input lines and at least one of the hydraulic sprayers to carry flow of coating to at least one of the hydraulic sprayers. 37. The method of claim 35 further including providing one or more valves to control flow from one or more input lines in the first input manifold to enable selection of flow of a type of coating into the at least one of the hydraulic sprayers. 38. The method of claim 35 further including controlling flow of coating with one or more valves to selectively deliver the coating to different hose lines. 39. The method of claim 35 where each tank has a holding capacity of at least 50 gallons. 40. The method of claim 35 where at least four tanks are mounted on the vehicle. 41. The method of claim 35 where the combined holding capacity of the tanks is at least 300 gallons. 42. A spray coating dispensing system, comprising: a vehicle; a series of tanks mounted on the vehicle, each tank configured to contain at least 30 gallons of coating; one or more first multi-port manifolds positioned on the vehicle; a plurality of hydraulic sprayers mounted on the vehicle, each connected to at least one tank via the multi-port manifold; a plurality of hoses, each connected to a sprayer and extendable from the sprayer a distance away from the vehicle, each hose designed to connect to a spray gun to apply a coating through a nozzle and on to a surface; 

 a plurality of hose reels mounted on the vehicle, each for holding a hose when the hose is not in use. 43. The system of claim 42 further including one or more second multi-port manifolds positioned on the vehicle and arranged in a flow path between the plurality of hydraulic sprayers and the plurality of hoses; a first plurality of flow control valves positioned to select among different flow paths through the one or more first manifolds and between the tanks and the sprayers; and a second plurality of flow control valves positioned to select among different flow paths through the one or more second manifolds and between the sprayers and the hoses. 44. A method of providing a liquid coating for application to surfaces from a coating operations vehicle, comprising: providing a first vehicle having plurality of tanks for receiving and dispensing the liquid mounted thereon, the vehicle including a plurality of hydraulic sprayers mounted on the first vehicle for powered operation to dispense the liquid from the mounted tanks when applying the liquid to a surface via a plurality of feed lines connected to extend from the mounted sprayers to a distance away from the first vehicle where the coating is to be applied; providing a second vehicle having at least one tank for receiving and dispensing the liquid mounted thereon; positioning the first vehicle at a location at which a supply of the coating is present for transfer into the tanks; positioning a second vehicle at the location at which the supply of the coating is present for transfer into the at least one tank; using a draw pump mounted on the first vehicle and one or more draw tubes to transfer the coating from the supply to the tanks mounted on the first vehicle; providing a first manifold connected between the draw pump and the tanks mounted on the first vehicle, the first manifold including multiple first fill lines, each extending to one of the tanks mounted on the first vehicle; positioning a fill valve in each first fill line for (i) control of flow of the coating into at least one of the tanks mounted on the first vehicle or (ii) selection of a tank mounted on the first vehicle for receipt of the coating material, said control and selection enabling transfer of different coating types into different tanks mounted on the first vehicle via the one or more draw tubes; and 

 using the draw pump mounted on the first vehicle and one or more draw tubes to transfer the coating from the supply to the at least one tank mounted on the second vehicle. 45. The method of clam 44 where multiple tanks are mounted on the second vehicle, the method further including connecting a second manifold between the draw pump and the tanks mounted on the second vehicle, the second manifold including multiple second fill lines, each extending to one of the tanks mounted on the second vehicle; and using the draw pump mounted on the first vehicle and one or more draw tubes to transfer the coating from the supply to multiple tanks mounted on the second vehicle. 46. The method of claim 45 where using the draw pump mounted on the first vehicle to transfer the coating from the supply to the multiple tanks mounted on the second vehicle further includes positioning a fill valve in each second fill line for (i) control of flow of the coating into at least one of the tanks mounted on the second vehicle or (ii) selection of a tank mounted on the second vehicle for receipt of the coating material, said control and selection enabling transfer of different coating types into different tanks mounted on the second vehicle via the one or more draw tubes. 47. The method of claim 46 where using the draw pump mounted on the first vehicle and one or more draw tubes to transfer the coating from the supply to multiple one of the tanks mounted on the second vehicle includes transfer of different coating types into different tanks mounted on the second vehicle. 48. A method for dispensing a coating comprising: a) connecting an input manifold of a paint sprayer on a vehicle to a plurality of tanks mounted on the vehicle; b) connecting an output of the paint sprayer to a plurality of hoses mounted on reels which are mounted on the vehicle; c) opening an output valve of at least one of the plurality of tanks; d) opening an input valve of at least one of the plurality of hoses; e) drawing paint into the paint sprayer through the intake manifold from the at least one of the plurality of tanks; and f) delivering paint from the paint sprayer output to the at least one of the plurality of hoses. 49. The method of claim 48, further comprising: g) extending the at least one hose from the vehicle to at least one location external to the vehicle around a job site; and h) spraying paint with a spray gun attached to the at least one hose at the at least one location around the job site. 50. The method of claim 49, wherein the at least one hose is at least two hoses, wherein step g) comprises extending the at least two hoses from the vehicle to at least two different locations away from the vehicle and around the job site and wherein step h) comprises spraying paint from the at least two hoses at the at least two different locations around the job site. 51. The method of claim 50, wherein the at least two different locations around the job site comprise at least one location external to a building at the job site and at least one location within an interior of the building at the job site. 52. The method of claim 48, wherein step a) comprises connecting the input manifold to the plurality of tanks with feed lines and wherein the method further comprises: securing an overflow tank to the vehicle; connecting the paint sprayer to the overflow tank through an overflow line with a primer valve; turning off the paint sprayer; and opening the primer valve to release high pressure within the feed lines to the overflow tank. 53. The method of claim 52, wherein securing the overflow tank to the vehicle comprises securing the overflow tank within a recess in the vehicle. 54. The method of claim 48, wherein step a) comprises connecting the input manifold of a first paint sprayer to a first plurality of tanks on the vehicle and connecting the input manifold of a second paint sprayer to a second plurality of tanks on the vehicle, wherein the first and second plurality of tanks have a level of paint at a desired level; wherein step b) comprises connecting the output of the first paint sprayer to a first plurality of hoses on reels mounted on the vehicle and connecting the output of the second paint sprayer to a second plurality of hoses mounted on reels on the vehicle; 

 wherein step c) comprises opening the output valve of at least one of the first plurality of tanks and opening the output valve of at least one of the second plurality of tanks; wherein step d) comprises opening the input valve of at least one of the first plurality of hoses on reels mounted on the vehicle and opening the input valve of at least one of the second plurality of hoses on reels; wherein step e) comprises drawing paint into the first paint sprayer through the intake manifold from the at least one of the first plurality of tanks and drawing paint into the second paint sprayer through the intake manifold from the at least one of the second plurality of tanks based on step c); and wherein step f) comprises delivering paint from the first paint sprayer output to the at least one of the first plurality of hoses on reels and delivering paint from the second paint sprayer output to the at least one of the second plurality of hoses on reels based on step d). 55. The method of claim 54, wherein the paint in the first plurality of tanks is a first color paint and the paint in the second plurality of tanks is a second color paint different than the first color paint. 56. The method of claim 48, wherein step f) comprises maximizing a flow rate of paint from the paint sprayer based on step c) comprising opening the output valve of each of the plurality of tanks, wherein each of the plurality of tanks have a same color paint. 57. The method of claim 48, wherein step f) comprises assessing whether the at least one of the plurality of hoses is inoperable and closing an associated input valve if one of the hoses is inoperable. 58. The method of claim 48, wherein the method further comprises: positioning an auxiliary reservoir of lubricating fluid on the vehicle above the paint sprayer; connecting the auxiliary reservoir to a primary reservoir of lubricating fluid in the paint sprayer through a feed line; and directing lubricating fluid from the auxiliary reservoir to the primary reservoir in the paint sprayer until a level of lubricating fluid in the reservoir reaches a desired level. 59. The method of claim 58, wherein three or more paint sprayers are positioned on the vehicle, wherein the auxiliary reservoir is positioned above the three or more paint sprayers, wherein the auxiliary reservoir is connected to a respective primary reservoir in each of the three or more paint sprayers through three or more feeds lines, and wherein the method further comprises: opening a valve in fewer than the three or more feed lines; and 

 simultaneously directing lubricating fluid from the auxiliary reservoir to the primary reservoir in fewer than the three or more paint sprayers corresponding to the feed lines with the opened valve. 60. A method comprising: a) connecting a paint sprayer to a plurality of tanks on a vehicle through feed lines; b) connecting the paint sprayer to a plurality of hoses on reels which are mounted on the vehicle through feed lines; c) securing an overflow tank to the vehicle; d) connecting the paint sprayer to the overflow tank through an overflow line via a primer valve; e) drawing paint into the paint sprayer from at least one of the plurality of tanks; f) delivering paint from the paint sprayer to at least one of the plurality of the hoses; g) turning off the paint sprayer; and h) opening the primer valve to release high pressure within the feed lines to the overflow tank. 61. The method of claim 60, wherein step c) comprises securing the overflow tank within a recess on the vehicle. 62. A system comprising: a vehicle; a plurality of tanks on the vehicle, each tank including an output valve; a plurality of hoses mounted on reels which are mounted on the vehicle, flow through each hose controllable with an in-line input valve; a paint sprayer on the vehicle with an input manifold connected to the plurality of tanks and an output connected to the plurality of hose reels; wherein the paint sprayer is configured to draw paint through the intake manifold from at least one of the plurality tanks based on the output valve of the at least one tank being in an open position; and wherein the paint sprayer is configured to deliver paint from the output to at least one of the plurality of hoses based on the input valve of the at least one hose being n an open position. 63. The system of claim 62, wherein the at least one hose on a reel is a first hose of a first length and a second hose on a reel is of a second length that is greater than the first length; and wherein the first hose is configured to be extended from the vehicle to a first location external to the vehicle around a job site and wherein the second hose is configured to be extended from the vehicle to a second location external 

 to the vehicle around the job site, wherein the first location is closer to the vehicle than the second location. 64. The system of claim 62, further comprising: feed lines to connect the input manifold to the plurality of tanks; an overflow tank secured within a recess in the vehicle; and an overflow line with an in-line primer valve to connect the paint sprayer to the overflow tank, wherein the overflow line is configured to release high pressure within the feed lines to the overflow tank when the primer valve is in an open position. 65. The system of claim 62, further comprising: a first paint sprayer with a first input manifold connected to a first plurality of tanks on the vehicle and a first output connected to a first plurality of hoses on reels mounted on the vehicle; and a second paint sprayer with a second input manifold connected to a second plurality of tanks on the vehicle and a second output connected to a second plurality of hoses on reels mounted on the vehicle, wherein the first paint sprayer is configured to draw paint through the first intake manifold from at least one of the first plurality of tanks based on the output valve of the at least one first tank in the open position, and wherein the second paint sprayer is configured to draw paint through the second intake manifold from at least one of the second plurality of tanks based on the output valve of the at least one second tank in the open position, and wherein the first paint sprayer is configured to deliver paint to at least one of the first plurality of hoses based on the input valve of the at least one first hoses being in the open position and wherein the second paint sprayer is configured to deliver paint to at least one of the second plurality of hoses based on the input valve of the at least one second hose being in the open position. 66. The method of claim 23 further including pumping the coating into one or more of the tanks via the manifold.
